 may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Fowke was born about 1440, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Margaret Legh before 1464. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1483, in Staffordshire, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"abt 1440–1483":"umbes 1440–1483","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1464–1490":"1464–1490","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1500":"1500","before 1464":"enne 1464","1455":"1455","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","14